---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import FutureCharts from '../components/FutureCharts';
import { BarChart3, Users, Clock, Search, Shield, TrendingDown } from 'lucide-react';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

// Data from Frey & Osborne (2013) - "The Future of Employment"
const automationData = [
	{ category: 'Transportation & Logistics', risk: 0.79, jobs: 4700000 },
	{ category: 'Office & Administrative', risk: 0.96, jobs: 15000000 },
	{ category: 'Production & Manufacturing', risk: 0.72, jobs: 9000000 },
	{ category: 'Sales & Service', risk: 0.47, jobs: 12000000 },
	{ category: 'Food Service', risk: 0.73, jobs: 5000000 },
	{ category: 'Construction', risk: 0.70, jobs: 6000000 },
	{ category: 'Healthcare Support', risk: 0.30, jobs: 3000000 },
	{ category: 'Education & Training', risk: 0.20, jobs: 8000000 },
	{ category: 'Management', risk: 0.13, jobs: 6000000 },
	{ category: 'Creative & Arts', risk: 0.08, jobs: 2000000 },
	{ category: 'Engineering & Tech', risk: 0.15, jobs: 5000000 }
];

const totalJobs = automationData.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.jobs, 0);
const jobsAtRisk = automationData.reduce((sum, item) => sum + (item.jobs * item.risk), 0);
const percentAtRisk = Math.round((jobsAtRisk / totalJobs) * 100);
---

<Layout title="The Future of Employment - Made in America" showQuizBanner={false}>
	<div class="future-page">
		<!-- Hero Section -->
		<section class="infographic-hero">
			<div class="hero-title">The Future of Employment</div>
			<div class="hero-subtitle">A 2013 study predicts what automation means for American workers</div>
			<div class="hero-stat">
				<span class="hero-stat-number">{percentAtRisk}%</span>
				<span class="hero-stat-label">of U.S. jobs at risk</span>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Key Statistics -->
		<section class="infographic-stats">
			<div class="stat-card-large">
				<BarChart3 client:load class="stat-icon" size={32} />
				<div class="stat-number">{percentAtRisk}%</div>
				<div class="stat-label">At Risk</div>
				<div class="stat-description">702 occupations analyzed</div>
			</div>
			<div class="stat-card-large">
				<Users client:load class="stat-icon" size={32} />
				<div class="stat-number">{Math.round(jobsAtRisk / 1000000)}M</div>
				<div class="stat-label">Jobs Vulnerable</div>
				<div class="stat-description">Out of {Math.round(totalJobs / 1000000)}M total</div>
			</div>
			<div class="stat-card-large">
				<Clock client:load class="stat-icon" size={32} />
				<div class="stat-number">10-20</div>
				<div class="stat-label">Years</div>
				<div class="stat-description">Timeline for automation</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Research Overview -->
		<section class="infographic-research">
			<div class="research-header">
				<h2>The Study</h2>
				<p class="research-subtitle">Frey & Osborne (2013) • 702 U.S. Occupations</p>
			</div>
			<div class="research-grid">
				<div class="research-card">
					<Search client:load class="research-icon" size={28} />
					<h3>Methodology</h3>
					<p>Analyzed technical feasibility of automating 702 detailed occupations</p>
				</div>
				<div class="research-card">
					<Shield client:load class="research-icon" size={28} />
					<h3>Three Barriers</h3>
					<p>Perception & manipulation, creative intelligence, social intelligence</p>
				</div>
				<div class="research-card">
					<TrendingDown client:load class="research-icon" size={28} />
					<h3>Key Finding</h3>
					<p>Strong negative correlation: lower wages and education = higher automation risk</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="chart-section">
			<div class="section-header">
				<h2>Visualizing the Research</h2>
				<p class="section-subtitle">Interactive charts exploring automation risk, wages, and education</p>
			</div>

			<FutureCharts client:load automationData={automationData} />
		</section>

		<section class="analysis-section">
			<div class="analysis-content">
				<h2>The Grim Reality</h2>
				<p>
					The Frey-Osborne study reveals a troubling pattern: jobs requiring routine, repetitive tasks are most vulnerable. Office and administrative support workers face a <strong>96% probability</strong> of automation. Transportation and logistics workers face <strong>79%</strong>. Food service workers: <strong>73%</strong>. Production and manufacturing: <strong>72%</strong>.
				</p>
				<p>
					These aren't abstract numbers—they represent millions of Americans whose livelihoods hang in the balance. The study found a strong negative relationship between an occupation's probability of computerization and factors such as wages and educational attainment. In other words: <strong>the jobs most at risk are often the ones that pay the least and require the least education</strong>—precisely the jobs that many workers rely on to survive.
				</p>
				<p>
					While creative professions, management roles, and jobs requiring social intelligence show lower automation risk, these represent a smaller fraction of the labor market. The question becomes: what happens to the millions of workers displaced by automation? Will new jobs emerge fast enough? Or are we heading toward a future of mass unemployment and economic inequality?
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Historical Context -->
		<section class="infographic-timeline">
			<h2>History Repeats</h2>
			<div class="timeline-compact">
				<div class="timeline-item-compact">
					<span class="timeline-year">1820<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>-1880<span class="lowercase-s">s</span></span>
					<span class="timeline-text">Market Revolution: Machines replace artisans</span>
				</div>
				<div class="timeline-item-compact">
					<span class="timeline-year">1880<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>-1970<span class="lowercase-s">s</span></span>
					<span class="timeline-text">Industrial Era: Assembly lines replace craftspeople</span>
				</div>
				<div class="timeline-item-compact">
					<span class="timeline-year">1970<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>-2000<span class="lowercase-s">s</span></span>
					<span class="timeline-text">Post-Industrial: Manufacturing automated or offshored</span>
				</div>
				<div class="timeline-item-compact">
					<span class="timeline-year">2000<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>-Present</span>
					<span class="timeline-text">Digital Era: E-commerce, self-checkout, AI automation</span>
				</div>
				<div class="timeline-item-compact future-highlight">
					<span class="timeline-year">2020<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>-2030<span class="lowercase-s">s</span>?</span>
					<span class="timeline-text"><strong>47% of jobs at risk</strong> — Autonomous vehicles, AI office workers</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- The Question -->
		<section class="infographic-question">
			<div class="question-content">
				<h2>Will This Time Be Different?</h2>
				<p>Previous technological revolutions created new jobs as they destroyed old ones. But what if machines can now replace not just manual labor, but cognitive labor too?</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="citation-section">
			<div class="citation-content">
				<h3>Source</h3>
				<p>
					Frey, Carl Benedikt, and Michael A. Osborne. "The future of employment: how susceptible are jobs to computerisation?" <em>Technological Forecasting and Social Change</em> 114 (2013): 254-280.
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://oms-www.files.svdcdn.com/production/downloads/academic/The_Future_of_Employment.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="citation-link">
						Read the full study (PDF) →
					</a>
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>

